Chemical composition of the prepared N-CQDs as obtained from FT-IR spectrum (Fig. 1
                        ) suggest the presence of –COOH, –NH2, C–H, C=O, C–N and C–O functional groups. The presence of a very strong band at 3400 cm−1 is due to the (O–H)/(N–H) stretching vibrations. This is also accompanied by a strong (C=O) stretching frequency at 1645 cm−1. The small shoulder of this band that appears around 1700 cm−1 indicates the existence of different types of C=O functionalities on the surface. Presence of dopped nitrogen atoms is evidenced from the (C-N) stretching vibration that covers the 1380–1440 cm−1 region. Finally, (C-O) vibration frequencies of ether, ester and carboxylic are found from 1025 to 1150 cm−1 
                        [21,22]. The IR spectrum, thus indicates the presence of carboxyl, amino and hydroxy groups on the carbon cores of the dots which are responsible for their high solubility and good dispersion in water [23].

Further studies were performed by varying the concentration of ferric ions from 0 to 250 μM (Fig. 6
                        a) to explore and establish the concentration dependency. The PL response to Fe3+ concentration taken in terms of differential PL intensity (ΔF = F0-F, where F0 is the fluorescent intensity of the blank and F is the intensity in presence of Fe3+, Fig. 6b) reveals that a very good linear correlation exists in the concentration range 0–25 μM range (inset in Fig. 6b) with a correlation coefficient value of 0.9942. The limit of detection (LOD) was calculated using the formula LOD = 3σ/S, where σ is the standard deviation of the PL intensities of five blank samples and S is the slope of the linear correlation between the concentration of Fe3+ ions and PL response [36]. The value of LOD by this method was found to be 0.257 μM which was well below the permissible limit of 3.57 μM/L set by the European Union [37] and is also lower than many recent reports in which carbon quantum dots are used for the detection of Fe3+ ions (Table 1
                        ).
